Rabbit haemorrhagic disease, Canada
-----------------------------------
Information received on 12 May 2011 from Dr Brian Evans, Chief Food
Safety Officer/Chief Veterinary Officer, Office of the President,
Canadian Food Inspection Agency, Ottawa, Canada

Summary
Report type Immediate notification (Final report)
Start date 29 Mar 2011
Date of 1st confirmation of the event 14 Apr 2011
Report date 12 May 2011
Date submitted to OIE 12 May 2011
Date event resolved 30 Mar 2011
Reason for notification 1st occurrence of a listed disease
Manifestation of disease Clinical disease
Causal agent Calicivirus
Nature of diagnosis Laboratory (advanced), Necropsy
This event pertains to the whole country

New outbreaks
Outbreak 1 (RHD-2011-MB-001) Winnipeg, Manitoba
Date of start of the outbreak 29 Mar 2011
Outbreak status Resolved (30 Mar 2011)
Epidemiological unit Not applicable
Affected animals
Species Rabbits
Susceptible 3
Cases 1
Deaths 1
Destroyed 0
Slaughtered 0

Affected Population: The infected animal is a pet rabbit that was
kept in an apartment in the city of Winnipeg with 2 other pet rabbits.
The infected animal was purchased in a pet store in the spring of
2010. The 3 rabbits have no access to outdoors and no contact with
other domestic or wild rabbits. This is a non-commercial pet related
event.

Epidemiology - Source of the outbreak(s) or origin of infection.
Unknown or inconclusive

Epidemiological comments: In late March 2011 a neutered male domestic
pet rabbit, over one year in age, displayed lethargy for a short
period of time. Yellow matter was observed on its fur. On 30 Mar 2011
it was presented to a local veterinary clinic where it was diagnosed
with liver failure and died during treatment. The body was forwarded
to the Manitoba Ministry of Agriculture, Food and Rural Initiatives
(MAFRI) laboratory. Findings included jaundice, hepatic necrosis, some
haemorrhages, moderate meningoencephalitis, and mild nephritis. Fixed
and fresh liver was sent to the CFIA National Center for Foreign
Animal Diseases (NCFAD) to rule out rabbit haemorrhagic disease (RHD)
virus. The body was cremated.

On 14 and 15 Apr 2011 the NCFAD reported positive results for RHD
virus by conventional RT-PCR and the finding of a Calicivirus-like
agent by electron microscopy. The nucleotide sequence had the closest
match in Genbank with an RHD virus isolate from China from 2006. On 20
and 21 Apr 2011, histopathology confirmed lesions consistent with RHD
and positive staining for RHD virus antigens was shown by
immunohistochemistry.

Rabbits were inoculated with material from the MAFRI submission on 26
Apr 2011. All inoculated rabbits were strongly positive for RHD virus
by conventional RT-PCR. Histopathology on tissue from the inoculated
rabbits showed lesions consistent with RHD. Immunohistochemistry on
liver, spleen and kidney from inoculated rabbits showed positive
immunoreactivity for RHD virus and electron microscopy of a liver
homogenate was positive for Calicivirus-like particles. Sequencing of
the PCR amplicons from liver material from the 3 inoculated rabbits
was 100% identical with one another as well as the original amplicon
from the submitted rabbit.

The infected rabbit was kept in an apartment with 2 other pet rabbits
for more than one year before he got sick. They had no contact with
commercial or wild rabbits.

After confirmation of the diagnosis on the index case, the 2 other
pet rabbits were inspected and tested by the Canadian Food Inspection
Agency (CFIA) with negative results (RT-PCR on blood and cELISA for
antibodies -- results released on 6 May 2011. As of today, these 2
rabbits remain clinically healthy.

The apartment owners had cleaned and disinfected the cage and the
contact areas of the infected rabbit. CFIA considers this event in a
non-commercial rabbit as resolved.

Control measures: Measures applied - Disinfection of infected
premises/establishment(s); Vaccination prohibited; No treatment of
affected animals

Measures to be applied - No other measures

Laboratory name and type: Manitoba Ministry of Agriculture, Food and
Rural Initiatives (MAFRI) (Local laboratory
Species Rabbits
Test histopathological examination
Test date 13 Apr 2011
Result Doubtful (uncertain)

Laboratory name and type CFIA National Centre for Foreign Animal
Diseases - Winnipeg (National laboratory)

Species Rabbits
Test gene sequencing
Test date 15 Apr 2011
Result Positive

Species Rabbits
Test histopathological examination
Test date 20 Apr 2011
Result Positive

Species Rabbits
Test immunohistochemical test
Test date 21 Apr 2011
Result Positive

Species Rabbits
Test inoculation test
Test date 02 May 2011
Result Positive

Species Rabbits
Test reverse transcription - polymerase chain reaction (RT-PCR)
Test date 14 Apr 2011
Result Positive

Future Reporting
The event is resolved. No more reports will be submitted.

